The first flight in the government’s controversial plan to send asylum seekers to Rwanda has been given the green light after a legal challenge to stop it failed. Judges sitting in the Court of Appeal refused an appeal to block the flight from taking off tomorrow. Under the plan, some of those who enter the UK via small boats or in lorries will flown to Rwanda where they will have their asylum applications processed. Boris Johnson said the government had expected “a lot of teething problems” with the policy but said it was necessary to stop illegal people-smuggling rackets on either side of the Channel. This is a breaking news story and will be updated. Follow HuffPost UK on Twitter, Facebook and Instagram.